Class → Blueprint
Fields → Data
Constructor → Initialization
Methods → Behavior
Object → Real usage

Student s = new Student();
s.id = 1;
s.name = "Om";

- this is bad idea to initialise the values so that is why we create a constructor to provide data at the time of creation.
- means avoids partially initialized objects.

- ? - But here if we have to create more students we cannot create more object so we are using the ArrayList which is resizable class.

    Example: ArrayList list = new ArrayList();
- also if we write like this will create problem because it called as without using the generics means we can add any type
  of data or object in it which is unsafe.

    Example: <Student> is a generic type parameter
- but if we use so this ArrayList will store ONLY Student objects
- Student is a class, You want this list to store Student objects
    students.add(new Student()); // ✅ allowed
    students.add("Hello");       // ❌ compile-time error
    students.add(10);            // ❌ compile-time error
- Generics provide type safety at compile time

Q: Why we not passing any datatype like int, String or any?
-> Because generics work only with reference types, NOT primitives. (Generics work only with objects, not primitives)
    Example: ArrayList<int> list;   // ❌ compile-time error
             ArrayList<Integer> list;

Imp: What happens INTERNALLY?
- JVM creates an ArrayList object
- Generic type <Student> is used by compiler only
- At runtime, type erasure happens
- After compilation: ArrayList students = new ArrayList();
- Generics are removed at runtime (Type Erasure)

Q: Why generics don’t support primitives?
   ✔ Backward compatibility
   ✔ Type erasure
   ✔ Also generics works with objects only and primitives are not obejcts

